- "client_id" is a unique identifier for each client;
- "industry" refers to the sector or field of business the client operates in;
- "project_id" is a unique identifier for each project.

- "Fertile with bugs" refers to projects with a high number of bugs;
- "Pests have been tamed" refers to bugs that have been fixed;
- "Sown in each project" refers to the total number of test cases created for each project;
- "Success rate of the harvest" refers to the percentage of test cases that passed.

- A project's milestone completion rate is calculated as the percentage of completed milestones out of the total milestones;
- The average velocity and burn rate provide insights into the project's progress and efficiency;
- The total number of bugs, test cases released, and test cases in software are indicators of the project's quality and testing efforts.

- "Multiple instances" refers to projects that have the same name but different IDs, indicating they are repeated or have multiple versions;
- "Above-average velocity" means the project's velocity is higher than the average velocity of all projects in the database;
- "Most productive developers" are those who have completed the highest number of tasks in their respective projects.

- Velocity in project management often refers to the speed at which a project is progressing, typically measured by the amount of work completed in a given time period;
- Burn rate in project management refers to the rate at which resources (such as budget or time) are being consumed;
- Ranking in the top 3 for both velocity and burn rate indicates that these projects are highly active and resource-intensive.

- 'Velocity' refers to the speed at which a project is progressing, typically measured by the amount of work completed in a given time period;
- 'Burn rate' is the rate at which a project is spending resources, often used to track financial expenditures but can also refer to the rate of work completion or issue resolution;
- 'Severity' of a bug indicates the impact of the bug on the project, with 'high' indicating a critical issue, 'medium' a significant issue, and 'low' a minor issue.

- "tech-savvy clients" refers to clients from the technology industry;
- "developmental gardens" refers to projects with names containing the word "Development";
- "bugs sown" refers to bugs reported by the client in the project.

- 'Higher number of tasks' refers to projects with more than 5 distinct tasks;
- 'Unique bugs' are bugs that are distinct within the project;
- 'Average number of tasks per project' is calculated by dividing the total number of distinct tasks by the number of distinct projects.

- "Garden" refers to a project;
- "Flowers" refer to test cases;
- "Seeds" refer to test case scripts.

- "high velocity" typically refers to a value greater than 50;
- "low burn rate" typically refers to a value less than 30;
- "software development projects" are projects that include the phrase "Software Development" in their names.

- "Completed task" refers to a task with a status of 'done';
- "Average number of bugs" is the mean count of bugs found in the projects;
- "Grouped by client and industry" means the data is aggregated based on the unique combination of a client and their industry.
